TY  - JOUR
T1  - Early Starters versus Late Beginners
AU  - Chiappori, Pierre‐Andre
AU  - Salanie, Bernard
AU  - Valentin, Julie
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250077
DO  - 10.1086/250077
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 731
EP  - 760
VL  - 107
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We consider a model of wage formation characterized by two features, learning and downward rigidity. We show that wages should exhibit a late?beginning property: when one controls for the wage at date t, the wage at date t + 1 should be negatively correlated with the wage at date 6?1. We test this property on a sample of about 1,000 executives of a French state?owned firm whose careers we observe for 15 years. This organization exhibits the features that charecterize internal labor markets; in particular, careers consist of sequences of discrete promotions, a fact that generates specific econometric problems. The results confirm the prediction.
AB  - We consider a model of wage formation characterized by two features, learning and downward rigidity. We show that wages should exhibit a late?beginning property: when one controls for the wage at date t, the wage at date t + 1 should be negatively correlated with the wage at date 6?1. We test this property on a sample of about 1,000 executives of a French state?owned firm whose careers we observe for 15 years. This organization exhibits the features that charecterize internal labor markets; in particular, careers consist of sequences of discrete promotions, a fact that generates specific econometric problems. The results confirm the prediction.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250077
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250077
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Theory and Evidence on the Political Economy of the Minimum Wage
AU  - Sobel, Russell S.
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250078
DO  - 10.1086/250078
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 761
EP  - 785
VL  - 107
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines how closely the minimum wage has been set to the most popularly stated goals of minimun?wage policy. I first estimate these goals: the minimum?wage rate at which the relevant labor demand is unitary elastic?maximizing the total earnings of minimum?wage workers (about $5.35)?and the level that would lift a typical minimum?wage worker's family out of poverty (about $5.17). I can reject that the actual minimum?wage policy has been driven by desire to achieve these goals and find that a simple interest group model best explains the historical path of the minimum?wage rate.
AB  - This paper examines how closely the minimum wage has been set to the most popularly stated goals of minimun?wage policy. I first estimate these goals: the minimum?wage rate at which the relevant labor demand is unitary elastic?maximizing the total earnings of minimum?wage workers (about $5.35)?and the level that would lift a typical minimum?wage worker's family out of poverty (about $5.17). I can reject that the actual minimum?wage policy has been driven by desire to achieve these goals and find that a simple interest group model best explains the historical path of the minimum?wage rate.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250078
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250078
Y2  - 2024/03/22
