TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dowry and Wife's Welfare: A Theotrical and Empirical Analysis
AU  - Zhang, Junsen
AU  - Chan, William
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250079
DO  - 10.1086/250079
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 786
EP  - 808
VL  - 107
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Becker attributes the existence of marital transfers to inflexibility in the division of joint product within the marriage. If that were the only reason, we would not have observed the coexistence of dowries and bride?prices. This paper offers an alternative analysis. While Becker's interpretation is retained for bride?prices, a dowry is now represented as a premortem bequest by altruistic parents for a daughter. It not only increases the wealth of the new conjugal household but also enhances the bargaining power of the bride in the allocation of the output within the household, thereby safeguarding here welfare. Using micro data from Taiwan, we found that a dowry improves the bride's welfare whereas a bride?price has no effect. These empirical results support the theoretical predictions of the model.
AB  - Becker attributes the existence of marital transfers to inflexibility in the division of joint product within the marriage. If that were the only reason, we would not have observed the coexistence of dowries and bride?prices. This paper offers an alternative analysis. While Becker's interpretation is retained for bride?prices, a dowry is now represented as a premortem bequest by altruistic parents for a daughter. It not only increases the wealth of the new conjugal household but also enhances the bargaining power of the bride in the allocation of the output within the household, thereby safeguarding here welfare. Using micro data from Taiwan, we found that a dowry improves the bride's welfare whereas a bride?price has no effect. These empirical results support the theoretical predictions of the model.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250079
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250079
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Defense Procurement Fraud, Penalties, and Contractor Influence
AU  - Karpoff, Jonathan M.
AU  - Lee, D. Scott
AU  - Vendrzyk, Valaria P.
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250080
DO  - 10.1086/250080
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 809
EP  - 842
VL  - 107
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Press reports of investigations of fraud, indictments, and suspensions in military procurement are associated with significantly negative average abnormal returns in the stocks of affected firms. Abnormal stock returns are significantly less negative, however, for firms ranking among the top 100 defense contractors than for unranked contractors, even after one controls for firm size, the frauds' characteristics, and the firm's recidivism. Unranked contractors are penalized heavily for procurment frauds, experiencing both a decline in market value and a subsequent loss in government?derived revenues. Furthermore, these losses are related to the percentage of the firm's revenues that derive from government contracts. Influential contractors, in contrast, are penalized lightly, experiencing negligible changes in share value and government contract revenue.
AB  - Press reports of investigations of fraud, indictments, and suspensions in military procurement are associated with significantly negative average abnormal returns in the stocks of affected firms. Abnormal stock returns are significantly less negative, however, for firms ranking among the top 100 defense contractors than for unranked contractors, even after one controls for firm size, the frauds' characteristics, and the firm's recidivism. Unranked contractors are penalized heavily for procurment frauds, experiencing both a decline in market value and a subsequent loss in government?derived revenues. Furthermore, these losses are related to the percentage of the firm's revenues that derive from government contracts. Influential contractors, in contrast, are penalized lightly, experiencing negligible changes in share value and government contract revenue.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250080
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250080
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Is the Standard Analysis of Common Property Extraction under Free Access Correct? A Game‐Theoretic Justification for Non‐Game‐Theoretic Analyses
AU  - Brooks, Robin
AU  - Murray, Michael
AU  - Salant, Stephen
AU  - Weise, Jill C.
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250081
DO  - 10.1086/250081
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 843
EP  - 858
VL  - 107
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Analyses of common property extraction under free access follow two distinct paths, traditional and game?theoretic, giving rise to two standard methodologies. One methodology avoids game?theoretic analysis by assuming that aggregate extraction in each period induces fel rent dissipation. The second methodology solves for the Marko?perfect equilibrium of an n?player extraction game investigating aggregate behavior over time as n ? ∞. We show by example that these coexisting standard methodologies can yield conflicting predictions. We then provide conditions, relatively easy to satisfy, sufficient for the two approaches to yield the same predictions.
AB  - Analyses of common property extraction under free access follow two distinct paths, traditional and game?theoretic, giving rise to two standard methodologies. One methodology avoids game?theoretic analysis by assuming that aggregate extraction in each period induces fel rent dissipation. The second methodology solves for the Marko?perfect equilibrium of an n?player extraction game investigating aggregate behavior over time as n ? ∞. We show by example that these coexisting standard methodologies can yield conflicting predictions. We then provide conditions, relatively easy to satisfy, sufficient for the two approaches to yield the same predictions.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250081
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250081
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - First‐Author Conditions
AU  - Engers, Maxim
AU  - Gans, Joshua S.
AU  - Grant, Simon
AU  - King, Stephen P.
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250082
DO  - 10.1086/250082
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 859
EP  - 883
VL  - 107
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper provides a theoretical explanation for the persistent use of alphabetical name ordering on academic papers in economics. In a context in which market participants are interested in evaluating the relative individual contribution of authors, it is an equilibrium for papers to use alphabetical ordering. Moreover, it is never an equilibrium for authors always to be listed in order of relative contribution. In fact, we show via an example that the alphabetical name ordering norm may be the unique equilibrium, althoug multiple equilibria are also possible. Finally, we charaterize the welfare properties of the noncooperative equilibrium and show it to produce research of lower quality than is optimal and than would be achieved if coauthors were forced to use name ordering to signal relative contribution.
AB  - This paper provides a theoretical explanation for the persistent use of alphabetical name ordering on academic papers in economics. In a context in which market participants are interested in evaluating the relative individual contribution of authors, it is an equilibrium for papers to use alphabetical ordering. Moreover, it is never an equilibrium for authors always to be listed in order of relative contribution. In fact, we show via an example that the alphabetical name ordering norm may be the unique equilibrium, althoug multiple equilibria are also possible. Finally, we charaterize the welfare properties of the noncooperative equilibrium and show it to produce research of lower quality than is optimal and than would be achieved if coauthors were forced to use name ordering to signal relative contribution.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250082
Y2  - 2024/03/22
